                {
                    "type": "object",
                    "value": {
                        "id": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "telehealth-tips"
                        },
                        "thumbnail": {
                            "type": "image",
                            "value": {
                                "src": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "assets/lifestyle-people-emotions-casual-concept-confident-nice-smiling-asian-woman-cross-arms-chest-confident-ready-help-listening-coworkers-taking-part-conversation-lutguyc3.jpg"
                                },
                                "alt": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "Clinician ready to help during a telehealth visit"
                                }
                            }
                        },
                        "title": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "Getting the Most Out of Your Telehealth Appointment"
                        },
                        "publishedDate": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "February 28, 2026"
                        },
                        "body": {
                            "type": "richtext",
                            "value": "Telehealth has made psychiatric care more accessible, but a few simple preparations can help your visit feel just as personal and productive as an in-office session.\n\nFind a private, quiet space with a stable internet connection. Use headphones if possible to improve audio clarity and protect your privacy. Have any current medications, recent lab results, or notes about symptoms ready to share.\n\nTreat your telehealth visit like any other medical appointment: arrive a few minutes early, minimize distractions, and be open about what is working and what is not. Your clinician is there to partner with you, whether you connect through a screen or face to face."
                        },
                        "gallery": {
                            "type": "array",
                            "value": []
                        }
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "object",
                    "value": {
                        "id": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "medication-management-basics"
                        },
                        "thumbnail": {
                            "type": "image",
                            "value": {
                                "src": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "assets/portrait-laughing-young-man-jqhyg71p.jpg"
                                },
                                "alt": {
                                    "type": "string",
                                    "value": "Young adult smiling during a wellness conversation"
                                }
                            }
                        },
                        "title": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "Medication Management: What New Patients Should Know"
                        },
                        "publishedDate": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "value": "January 15, 2026"
                        },
                        "body": {
                            "type": "richtext",
                            "value": "Starting psychiatric medication can feel uncertain, especially if it is your first time. Our goal is to make the process clear, collaborative, and safe from your very first visit.\n\nDuring medication management appointments, we review how you are feeling, discuss benefits and side effects, and adjust your plan when needed. Follow-ups are scheduled regularly so we can monitor progress closely, especially in the early weeks of treatment.\n\nMedication is never one-size-fits-all. Your plan is built around your diagnosis, your preferences, and how your body responds over time. Questions are always welcome, and informed consent is part of every decision we make together."
                        },
